{{about|Afghanistan|the other use of the redirect|Minister for Water and Power (Pakistan)}} {{Infobox government agency |agency_name = Ministry of Energy and Water |type = |nativename = |nativename_a = |nativename_r = |logo = |logo_width = |logo_caption = |seal = |seal_width = |seal_caption = |picture = AF-water-power.jpg |picture_width = |picture_caption = Ministry of Energy and Water |formed = <!-- {{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD}} OR {{Start date and years ago|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> |preceding1 = |preceding2 = <!-- (etc.) --> |dissolved = |superseding = |jurisdiction = [[Politics of Afghanistan|Government of Afghanistan]] |headquarters = Darul Aman Road Kabul Afghanistan |coordinates = <!--{{coord|LATITUDE|LONGITUDE|type:landmark_region:US|display=inline,title}}--> |motto = |employees = |budget = |minister1_name = Minister Ali Ahmad Osmani |minister1_pfo = |minister2_name = |minister2_pfo = <!-- (etc.) --> |deputyminister1_name = |deputyminister1_pfo = |deputyminister2_name = |deputyminister2_pfo = <!-- (etc.) --> |chief1_name = |chief1_position = |chief2_name = |chief2_position = <!-- (etc.) --> |agency_type = |parent_department = |parent_agency = |child1_agency = |child2_agency = <!-- (etc.) --> |keydocument1 = <!-- (etc.) --> |website = http://mew.gov.af/en |footnotes = |map = |map_width = |map_caption = }}
The '''Afghan Ministry of Energy and Water''' is a [[Government ministries of Afghanistan|ministry]] of the [[government of Afghanistan]]. Following the [[War in Afghanistan (2001–present)|U.S. invasion of Afghanistan]] the ministry had the task of co-ordinating an effort to reintroduce power to areas of [[Afghanistan]] that had been cut off. Areas particularly badly affected were southern [[regions of Afghanistan|regions]] - Pakistan,<ref name="DailyNewsPakistan">{{cite web |last=Syrian Arab News Agency (SANA) |first= |authorlink= |title=Pakistan to supply power to Afghanistan |publisher=''[[Daily Times (Pakistan)]]'' |date=16 March 2003 |url=http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=story_16-3-2003_pg5_11 |accessdate=2010-02-03 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606125330/http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=story_16-3-2003_pg5_11 |archivedate=2011-06-06 |df= }}</ref> Iran and India<ref name="AfghaCom">{{cite web |last = Staff |first = |authorlink = |title = Unknown |publisher = ''Afgha.com'' |date = |url = http://www.afgha.com/?af=article&sid=14384 |accessdate = 2010-02-03 |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110518072619/http://www.afgha.com/?af=article&sid=14384 |archivedate = 2011-05-18 |df = }} Web site simply returns "It works!" </ref> all agreed to supply power. On 17 June 2003 the [[Asian Development Bank]] agreed to give a loan of $50 million ([[USD]]) to the Afghan Ministry of Energy and Water. The loan would be spent over the next three years on projects for the production, distribution and transmission of electricity in Afghanistan.
Previous [[Ismail Khan]] served as Minister from 2004 – October 2013, being succeeded by [[Mohammad Arif Noorzai]] from 28 October 2013 – November 2014.
